 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.933864137858904*^9, {3.933892697903843*^9, 3.93389269818321*^9}, {
   3.9338935228570843`*^9, 3.9338935232235527`*^9}, {3.933893571766711*^9, 
   3.933893571936788*^9}, {3.933894389394203*^9, 3.933894389586187*^9}, {
   3.936718476143723*^9, 3.936718476564096*^9}, {3.9368897611829042`*^9, 
   3.936889761403069*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"44e673cc-b3ae-4d01-9a58-\
1edab02380f4"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Notes:",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "\nAll functions in (Red lines in: a,c,e) will be constructed using ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    OverscriptBox["f", "\[RightVector]"], "=", 
    RowBox[{
     OverscriptBox["X", "\[LeftRightVector]"], 
     OverscriptBox["a", "\[RightVector]"]}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"fc4d68fe-0d71-4f9f-8dc1-075355f13080"],
 ", ",
 StyleBox["with random coefficients",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " in ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   OverscriptBox["a", "\[RightVector]"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "bdc50120-17e4-48db-9bd4-d4caec3d05f7"],
 ". In other words, if you run your code twice, you will get two different \
results. The matrix ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   OverscriptBox["X", "\[LeftRightVector]"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "534e9b4c-93de-4c7b-9c24-9caba869bd80"],
 " has elements ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["X", 
     RowBox[{"i", ",", "j"}]], "=", 
    SubsuperscriptBox["x", "i", 
     RowBox[{"j", "-", "1"}]]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "4d2cd8d9-71ed-4d95-93c7-b510fa998aa8"],
 " as written in \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]Least Squares Approach: Polynomials\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]. You will then solve for the coefficients using \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]Artificial Neural Network (ANN) Approach: Polynomials.\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.933787328744812*^9, 3.933787331032897*^9}, 
   3.933787450354896*^9, {3.933847089431265*^9, 3.933847100141645*^9}, {
   3.9338471402285748`*^9, 3.9338471906279573`*^9}, {3.933856666973029*^9, 
   3.933856827184112*^9}, {3.9338569982447653`*^9, 3.9338569987683773`*^9}, {
   3.933858611750474*^9, 3.9338586372512503`*^9}, {3.933859646917585*^9, 
   3.933859725679678*^9}, {3.933859763289627*^9, 3.93385980460034*^9}, {
   3.9338601464705467`*^9, 3.933860160874807*^9}, {3.9338602365842247`*^9, 
   3.933860301912571*^9}, {3.933895949294146*^9, 3.933895979097889*^9}, {
   3.933896013237796*^9, 
   3.93389602601427*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"e93bb45d-b1ba-4fbd-8f2c-\
e8ecf68b9b67"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "All plots in the left column show the function to be fitted in red, with \
the fitted model-function in blue diamonds. Plots in the same row are \
associated with the title given in the left column. For example, Plot (a) and \
(b) describe the results for an exactly determined system of equations using \
polynomials as the basis functions.\n\nPlot (a) shows the scenario where the \
system is exactly determined i.e., the same number of equations as \
coefficients. Plot (b) shows the true coefficients in blue bars while the \
fitted coefficients are shown in the red bars along with the associated error \
in yellow. The error is the absolute value of the difference between the true \
and fitted coefficients. ",
 StyleBox["Plot (a) and Plot (b) employ a ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["6", "th"], TraditionalForm]],
  FontWeight->"Bold",ExpressionUUID->"bb1e2e50-ae63-49d6-b77b-6c5411ae3070"],
 StyleBox[" order polynomial to both construct the function to be fitted and \
for the solution to the least squares problem.",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "\n\nPlot (c) shows the scenario where the system is over determined i.e., \
more equation than coefficients. Plot (d) shows the true coefficients in blue \
bars while the fitted coefficients are shown in the red bars along with the \
associated error in yellow. The error is the difference between the true and \
fitted coefficients. ",
 StyleBox["Plot (c) and Plot (d) employ a ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["6", "th"], TraditionalForm]],
  FontWeight->"Bold",ExpressionUUID->"b0fc102c-9698-4e18-8a70-8340eea28196"],
 StyleBox[" order polynomial to construct the function to be fitted and an ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["8", "th"], TraditionalForm]],
  FontWeight->"Bold",ExpressionUUID->"afb38297-fe4d-42d8-a07f-9272fcab4029"],
 StyleBox[" order polynomial for the solution to the least squares problem.\n\
\n",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "Plot (e) shows the scenario where the system is under determined i.e., \
fewer equation than coefficients. Plot (f) shows the true coefficients in \
blue bars while the fitted coefficients are shown in the red bars along with \
the associated error in yellow. The error is the difference between the true \
and fitted coefficients. ",
 StyleBox["Plot (e) and Plot (f) employ a ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["6", "th"], TraditionalForm]],
  FontWeight->"Bold",ExpressionUUID->"e4aaffe3-42f4-4782-b939-61b0f081566c"],
 StyleBox[" order polynomial to construct the function to be fitted and an ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["5", "th"], TraditionalForm]],
  FontWeight->"Bold",ExpressionUUID->"68a44a39-7d2b-4f70-9288-57926ff43908"],
 StyleBox[" order polynomial for the solution to the least squares problem.",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "\n\nPlot (g) shows the scenario where the function to be fitted is a \
non-polynomial function and given by the MatLab equation:\n\n",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"f", "(", "x", ")"}], " ", "=", " ", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{
         RowBox[{
          RowBox[{"cos", "(", 
           RowBox[{"2", "*", "pi", "*", "6", "*", 
            RowBox[{"x", "/", "xMax"}]}], ")"}], "."}], "*", 
         RowBox[{"exp", "(", 
          RowBox[{
           RowBox[{"-", "5"}], "*", 
           RowBox[{
            RowBox[{"abs", "(", "x", ")"}], "/", "xMax"}]}], ")"}]}], "+", 
        RowBox[{
         RowBox[{
          RowBox[{"sin", "(", 
           RowBox[{"2", "*", "pi", "*", "3", "*", 
            RowBox[{"x", "/", "xMax"}]}], ")"}], "."}], "*", 
         RowBox[{"exp", "(", 
          RowBox[{
           RowBox[{"-", "2"}], "*", 
           RowBox[{
            RowBox[{"abs", "(", "x", ")"}], "/", "xMax"}]}], ")"}]}]}], ")"}],
       "'"}]}], ";"}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "161ca251-7afb-488b-a93b-b18906519a1c"],
 "\n\nPlot (h) shows the error between the original function (f(x) above) and \
the reconstructed function from the polynomial fit. The error is the absolute \
value of the difference between the original and fitted function at each \
point. ",
 StyleBox["Plot (g-h) employ a ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["12", "th"], TraditionalForm]],
  FontWeight->"Bold",ExpressionUUID->"4e5ee96a-aa03-4449-8ed3-507f79dff8b8"],
 StyleBox[" order polynomial for the solution to the fitting problem using \
ANNs.",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " Note how, even though a ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["12", "th"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "2239697b-f112-408b-a164-e161afc88155"],
 " order polynomial was used",
 "...this is not a good model for the given function, which is composed of \
sinusoids and strictly decaying exponentials. ",
 StyleBox["Most physical processes are well described by polynomials of order \
6 or less.",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "\n\nPlot (i) also shows the scenario where the function to be fitted is a \
non-polynomial function and given by the f(x) equation above. However, in \
this case, the basis functions are cosines and sine functions. See the \
included MatLab code for more details. The function decomposition is written \
according to:\n\n",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"f", "(", "x", ")"}], "=", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      UnderscriptBox[
       OverscriptBox["\[CapitalSigma]", "N"], 
       RowBox[{"n", "=", "1"}]], 
      SubscriptBox["a", "n"], 
      RowBox[{"cos", "(", 
       RowBox[{"2", "\[Pi]", " ", 
        FractionBox["x", "xMax"], "n"}], ")"}]}], "+", 
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox["b", "n"], 
      RowBox[{"sin", "(", 
       RowBox[{"2", "\[Pi]", " ", 
        FractionBox["x", "xMax"], "n"}], ")"}]}]}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"fb8ac606-d6a4-4093-bd51-ee6bbb7bf566"],
 "\n\nNote that the sum starts at ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"n", "=", "1"}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "670fd488-be6d-4256-8220-0f3a074af9e0"],
 " and does not include the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"n", "=", "0"}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "7a759f6b-efd0-41d0-9de9-e19147f1833f"],
 " (which is the same as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["a", "0"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "9d4cfacd-f77f-445f-b141-290ae0e63363"],
 ") term. That term is taken into account by the bias in the neural \
network.",
 " ",
 "Plot (j) shows the ",
 StyleBox["complex",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " Fourier  coefficients from the ANN solution. The complex coefficients are \
constructed from the cosine and sine Fourier series coefficients according \
to: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fourier_series#Exponential_form_\
coefficients\n\n",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["c", "n"], "\[Congruent]", 
    TagBox[GridBox[{
       {"\[Piecewise]", GridBox[{
          {
           SubscriptBox["a", "0"], 
           RowBox[{"n", "=", "0"}]},
          {
           RowBox[{
            FractionBox["1", "2"], 
            RowBox[{"(", 
             RowBox[{
              SubscriptBox["a", "n"], "-", 
              RowBox[{"\[ImaginaryI]", " ", 
               SubscriptBox["b", "n"]}]}], ")"}]}], 
           RowBox[{"n", ">", "0"}]},
          {
           SubsuperscriptBox["c", 
            RowBox[{"\[LeftBracketingBar]", "n", "\[RightBracketingBar]"}], 
            "*"], 
           RowBox[{"n", "<", "0"}]}
         },
         AllowedDimensions->{2, Automatic},
         Editable->True,
         GridBoxAlignment->{
          "Columns" -> {{Left}}, "ColumnsIndexed" -> {}, 
           "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}, "RowsIndexed" -> {}},
         GridBoxItemSize->{
          "Columns" -> {{Automatic}}, "ColumnsIndexed" -> {}, 
           "Rows" -> {{1.}}, "RowsIndexed" -> {}},
         GridBoxSpacings->{"Columns" -> {
             Offset[0.27999999999999997`], {
              Offset[0.84]}, 
             Offset[0.27999999999999997`]}, "ColumnsIndexed" -> {}, "Rows" -> {
             Offset[0.2], {
              Offset[0.4]}, 
             Offset[0.2]}, "RowsIndexed" -> {}},
         Selectable->True]}
      },
      GridBoxAlignment->{
       "Columns" -> {{Left}}, "ColumnsIndexed" -> {}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}, 
        "RowsIndexed" -> {}},
      GridBoxItemSize->{
       "Columns" -> {{Automatic}}, "ColumnsIndexed" -> {}, "Rows" -> {{1.}}, 
        "RowsIndexed" -> {}},
      GridBoxSpacings->{"Columns" -> {
          Offset[0.27999999999999997`], {
           Offset[0.35]}, 
          Offset[0.27999999999999997`]}, "ColumnsIndexed" -> {}, "Rows" -> {
          Offset[0.2], {
           Offset[0.4]}, 
          Offset[0.2]}, "RowsIndexed" -> {}}],
     "Piecewise",
     DeleteWithContents->True,
     Editable->False,
     SelectWithContents->True,
     Selectable->False,
     StripWrapperBoxes->True]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "72513213-5c90-4496-98e5-bdfc3b443a9a"],
 "\n\n",
 StyleBox["There are as many Fourier series coefficients as pixels in the \
original function. In other words, the basis matrix is square. ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "In contrast to polynomial fitting, there are often very high frequency \
components in signals we would like to fit. The blue asterisks in (j) were \
calculated using a DFT matrix, which is the same as MatLab\[CloseCurlyQuote]s \
dftmtx."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.933692659348854*^9, 3.933692686882187*^9}, {
   3.933694377227049*^9, 3.933694438748076*^9}, {3.933694583024501*^9, 
   3.93369475960769*^9}, {3.933694889455358*^9, 3.933694894174077*^9}, {
   3.9336960394203777`*^9, 3.933696039614101*^9}, {3.9336960829336443`*^9, 
   3.933696240578474*^9}, {3.9336962934805*^9, 3.933696357169565*^9}, 
